node.text:
Earlier, we were at Canaveral National Seashore. Watch as teams release these rehabilitated sea turtles into the ocean! 🐢 @turtlesfly2 

These sea turtles suffered from cold-stunning in the northeast, were rehabilitated to health and are now swimming in the warm Florida water. This puts them back in the habitat where they should be this time of year, giving them a better chance for survival.

All marine turtle footage/images was obtained with the approval of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) under conditions not harmful to marine turtles. Footage was acquired while conducting authorized conservation activities pursuant to: FWC 2021 Consent Permit, MTP-21-005 and MTP-21-114.

node.title: Join us as we launch rehabilitated sea turtles back into the ocean!

node.text:
We’re driving from the Launch and Landing Facility at Kennedy Space Center to Canaveral National Seashore with veteran NASA astronaut @astro_nicole to release rehabilitated sea turtles into the ocean.

These sea turtles suffered from cold-stunning in the northeast, were rehabilitated to health and are now swimming in the warm Florida water. This puts them back in the habitat where they should be this time of year, giving them a better chance for survival. @turtlesfly2 

All marine turtle footage/images was obtained with the approval of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) under conditions not harmful to marine turtles. Footage was acquired while conducting authorized conservation activities pursuant to: FWC 2021 Consent Permit, MTP-21-005 and MTP-21-114.

node.title: Let’s chat sea turtles with veteran NASA astronaut Nicole Stott!

node.text:
We’re here at the Launch and Landing Facility as rehabilitated sea turtles arrive from Cape Cod, Mass., and New York to be released in the warmer waters of the Space Coast. 🐢 @turtlesfly2 

These sea turtles suffered from cold-stunning in the northeast, were rehabilitated to health and are now swimming in the warm Florida water. This puts them back in the habitat where they should be this time of year, giving them a better chance for survival.

All marine turtle footage/images was obtained with the approval of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) under conditions not harmful to marine turtles. Footage was acquired while conducting authorized conservation activities pursuant to: FWC 2021 Consent Permit, MTP-21-005 and MTP-21-114.

node.title: The sea turtles have landed at the Launch and Landing Facility!

node.text: Take a look at the exciting activities taking place at America's multi-user spaceport as we prepare to fly astronauts to space from U.S. soil. once again.

node.text:
🚀🌕 We’re over the Moon to see you, Victor Glover and Christina Koch! 

@NASAAstronauts Victor Glover and Christina Koch recently took some time to check out the Space Launch System (SLS) rocket inside of the Vehicle Assembly Building. The rocket behind them will soon lift off from Kennedy Space Center’s Launch Complex 39B and send the Orion spacecraft around the Moon on the #Artemis I mission.
 
Both Glover and Koch are part of the @NASAArtemis Team – the initial group of @NASA astronauts that’ll help pave the way for the next lunar missions.
 
Artemis I will be a test of Orion and SLS as an integrated system ahead of crewed flights to the Moon. Under Artemis, NASA aims to land the first woman and first person of color on the Moon and establish long-term lunar exploration.
 
📸 Photo Credit:
1️⃣: NASA/Kim Shiflett
2️⃣: NASA/Glenn Benson

node.text:
🚀🤔 What’s happening inside of the Vehicle Assembly Building?
 
Within the 525-foot-tall building, you’ll find @NASA’s Space Launch System (SLS) rocket – a super-heavy-lift launch vehicle that will provide the foundation for human exploration beyond Earth’s orbit. Soon, the Orion spacecraft will join the already stacked flight hardware, marking the final assembly milestone for the #Artemis rocket.
 
SLS will launch America into a new era of exploration to destinations beyond low Earth orbit. On its first flight, NASA will demonstrate the rocket’s heavy-lift capability and send an uncrewed Orion spacecraft into deep space.
 
📸: NASA/Ben Smegelsky

node.text:
🚀 Lucy, @NASA's first spacecraft to explore Jupiter's Trojan asteroids, arrived at Kennedy Space Center last week to begin final preparations for liftoff. The spacecraft will launch on a @ULALaunch Atlas V rocket from Cape Canaveral Space Force Station and the 23-day launch window opens on Oct. 16.
 
So what are the Trojan asteroids, you ask? They are remnants of our early solar system, now trapped in stable orbits associated with the giant planet Jupiter, forming two “swarms” that lead in front of and trail behind Jupiter in its path around the Sun. 

Over its twelve-year primary mission, Lucy will explore a record-breaking number of asteroids, flying by one main belt asteroid and seven Trojan asteroids.
 
📸: NASA/Kim Shiflett

UPDATE (8/3): NASA, Boeing and United Launch Alliance have scrubbed today's launch to the International Space Station due to unexpected valve position indications in the Starliner propulsion system. 

Once the issue has been resolved, a new launch date will be determined. Stay tuned.

🚀🌟 Tomorrow at 1:20 p.m. ET, @Boeing’s Starliner spacecraft will launch on a @ULALaunch Atlas V rocket from Space Launch Complex-41! Weather is currently 60% favorable for liftoff.

Starliner is scheduled to dock to the @ISS on Wednesday, Aug. 4 at about 1:37 p.m. ET.

The Orbital Flight Test-2 mission for @NASA’s Commercial Crew Program will test the end-to-end capabilities of Starliner from launch to docking to a return to Earth in the desert of the western United States.

📸: NASA/Aubrey Gemignani

node.text:
One year ago today, @NASA's Perseverance Mars rover lifted off from Space Launch Complex-41 on its journey to Mars. 🚀
 
The rover landed on the Red Planet on Feb. 18, 2021, and is now:

🔴 Studying Mars' Habitability
🦠 Seeking Signs of Past Microbial Life
🪨 Collecting Samples
👩🏼‍🚀 Preparing for Future Human Missions
 
Did you #CountdownToMars with us? Share your memories in the comments below!

📸: NASA/Tony Gray/Tim Powers

UPDATE (7/30): The launch of NASA's Boeing Orbital Flight Test-2 mission is now targeted for Tuesday, Aug. 3 at 1:20 p.m. ET. Live coverage will begin on NASA TV at 12:30 p.m. ET.

LAUNCH UPDATE ➡️ @NASA and @Boeing have decided to stand down from Friday’s launch attempt of the Orbital Flight Test-2 mission. Currently, the earliest available launch opportunity is 1:20 p.m. EDT Tuesday, Aug. 3.

The International Space Station team will use the time to continue working checkouts of the newly arrived Roscosmos Nauka multipurpose laboratory module (MLM) and to ensure the station will be ready for Starliner’s arrival.

📸: @ULALaunch

node.text:
🚀🌕 50 years ago today, Apollo 15 lifted off from Launch Pad 39A carrying @NASA astronauts David Scott, James Irwin and Al Worden!
 
Apollo 15 was the first mission designed to explore the Moon over longer periods, greater ranges and with more instruments for the collection of scientific data than on previous missions. The mission included the introduction of the Lunar Roving Vehicle that reached a top speed of 10 mph (16 kph) across the Moon's surface.

The primary goals for Apollo 15 were to observe the lunar surface, survey and sample material and surface features in the Hadley-Apennine region, setup and activate surface experiments and conduct in-flight experiments and photographic tasks from lunar orbit.
 
📸: NASA

node.text:
🚀 FIVE. MORE. DAYS. 

On Friday, July 30, @NASA’s @Boeing Orbital Flight Test-2 (OFT-2) mission will launch to the @ISS! 

OFT-2 will test the end-to-end capabilities of Starliner from launch to docking, atmospheric re-entry, and a desert landing in the western United States. OFT-2 will provide valuable data that will help NASA certify Boeing’s crew transportation system to carry astronauts to and from the space station.

Live coverage of the launch will begin at 2 p.m. ET on Friday, July 30. Liftoff is targeted for 2:53 p.m. ET. 

📸: Boeing/Damon Tucci

“After serving the world for over 30 years, the space shuttle earned its place in history and has come to a final stop.” – Christopher J. Ferguson 

#OTD in 2011, space shuttle Atlantis and the STS-135 crew touched down at Kennedy Space Center just before dawn, wrapping up the final mission of the 30-year Space Shuttle Program. 

STS-135 was the 33rd and final flight for Atlantis, which spent 307 days in space, orbited Earth 4,848 times and traveled 125,935,769 miles.
 
📸: NASA

🤝 Starliner, meet your ride to space – the Atlas V rocket.
 
Over the weekend, @Boeing’s CST-100 Starliner spacecraft made its way to @ULALaunch’s Vertical Integration Facility where it was lifted and secured atop the Atlas V. The joining of Atlas V and Starliner is a major milestone ahead of the second uncrewed flight test to demonstrate the system’s human transportation capabilities to the @ISS.
 
The Orbital Flight Test-2 mission is scheduled to launch on July 30 at 2:53 p.m. ET.
 
📸: United Launch Alliance

node.text:
⬆️ The place to be on launch day 
 
When the first test flight of the Space Launch System (SLS) rocket and the Orion spacecraft launches from Launch Pad 39B, a dedicated team of engineers will be working together inside of the Launch Control Center.
 
Recently, teams from Kennedy, @nasa_marshall and @nasajohnson came together to perform the first joint integrated launch countdown simulation for #Artemis I. The training exercise involved rehearsing all aspects of the launch countdown, from cryogenic loading – filling tanks in the SLS rocket’s core stage with liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen – to liftoff. These simulations will help certify that the launch team is ready for Artemis I.
 
📸: NASA/Ben Smegelsky

node.text:
Rollin’ right along 🚀🌙
 
@NASA’s Orion spacecraft recently completed fueling and servicing checks while inside the Multi-Payload Processing Facility and has now made it to the next stop on the path to the pad – the Launch Abort System Facility!
 
Here, teams will add the launch abort system atop the spacecraft ahead of integrating with the Space Launch System (SLS) rocket. The system is designed to pull crew away to safety from SLS in the event of an emergency during launch.
 
Launching in 2021, #Artemis I will be a test of the Orion spacecraft and SLS rocket as an integrated system ahead of crewed flights to the Moon.
 
📸: NASA/Cory S. Huston
